# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: steve-owens-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The **1987 Major League Baseball draft** is the process by which Major League Baseball (MLB) teams select athletes to play for their organization.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] High school seniors, college juniors and seniors, and anyone who had never played under a professional contract were considered eligible for the draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The 1987 MLB Draft took place as a conference call to the Commissioner of Baseball's office in New York from June 2–4.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] As opposed to the National Football League draft which appeared on ESPN, no network aired the MLB Draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The American League (AL) and the National League (NL) alternated picks throughout the first round; because an NL team drafted first in the 1986 MLB draft, an AL team had the first selection in 1987.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Having finished 67–95 in 1986, the Seattle Mariners had the worst record in the AL and thus obtained the first overall selection.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The second selection went to the Pittsburgh Pirates, who had the worst record in the NL.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] With the first overall pick, the Mariners drafted Ken Griffey Jr. from Moeller High School.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Griffey Jr. became a 13-time All-Star and helped Seattle make its first postseason appearance in franchise history.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Mark Merchant, the second overall pick, however, never played in a major league game.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Two years after he was drafted, the Pirates traded Merchant to Seattle, where he got to meet Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Chicago White Sox' first overall selection Jack McDowell won the 1993 Cy Young Award as Chicago made a League Championship Series appearance that year.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The total number of athletes drafted, 1,263, broke a record for the most players ever chosen in a draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] In total, 27 All-Stars were selected in 1987, although not all signed a professional contract.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] As of 2020, only three players from the draft has been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame– Craig Biggio, Griffey Jr, and Mike Mussina, though Mussina did not sign in this draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] As with prior drafts, the team with the worst overall record from the previous season was selected first, with teams from the AL and NL alternating picks.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] If two or more teams had the same record, the team with the worse record from two seasons prior would draft higher.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Because the Pittsburgh Pirates of the NL were selected first overall in 1986 Major League Baseball draft, an AL team had the first pick in the 1987 draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The final two selections in the first round both came from American League teams, as the AL had two more organizations than the NL.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The date of the draft was set for June 2–4, and would occur as a conference call to the Commissioner of Baseball's office in New York.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Unlike the 1987 NFL draft, which aired on ESPN, no network televised the MLB draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] High school seniors, college juniors and seniors, and anyone who had never played under a professional contract were considered eligible to be drafted.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] For the first time, junior college players would also be included in the June draft; in years past, teams would select junior college players in a separate draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] If a "type-A" player became a free agent, the team that lost the type-A player would receive the first-round draft pick from the team that signed the player, as well as a "sandwich pick" between the first and second rounds.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] If a "type-B" became a free agent, the team that lost him would receive a second-round pick from the team that signed the player.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] If a "type-C" became a free agent, the team that lost him would receive a compensation pick between the second and third rounds.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The top 13 selections were considered "protected picks" and exempt from this rule.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] With a record of 67–95, the Seattle Mariners ended the 1986 Major League Baseball season with the worst record in the AL and thus obtained the first overall selection.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The Mariners never had a winning record in the twelve years since the franchise's creation (their best winning percentage was .469, accomplished in 1982), and during the 1986 season, changed managers three times.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] In the NL, the Pirates finished with the league's worst record for the second year in a row and were given the second overall pick.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The 1986 World Series champion New York Mets drafted third-to-last, with the runner-up Boston Red Sox selecting last.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The Kansas City Royals had the most picks of any team, with 74; following the Royals, the Toronto Blue Jays made 71, and the Cincinnati Reds and New York Mets made 61 apiece.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The total number of players drafted, 1,263, broke a record for the most players ever selected in a draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The previous record of 1,162 was set during the 1967 draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The California Angels drafted the fewest future MLB players, with only four of their draftees appearing in an MLB game, while the Blue Jays and the Texas Rangers both drafted 13 future MLB players, the most of any team.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] With their first overall pick, the Mariners selected Ken Griffey Jr., an outfielder from Moeller High School.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Over his 22-year career, Griffey Jr. was elected to thirteen All-Star games, won seven Silver Slugger Awards, and helped Seattle make their first playoff appearance as a franchise during the 1995 season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] Mark Merchant, whom the Pirates drafted second overall, never played in an MLB game; two years after they drafted him, Pittsburgh traded Merchant to Seattle.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/1987-mlb-draft] The Pirates made the playoffs for three consecutive seasons from 1990 to 1992 but lost in the National League Championship Series all three years.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2002 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began in January 2002.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2002 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2002 College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series, which consisted of the eight remaining teams in the NCAA tournament, was held in its annual location of Omaha, Nebraska, at Rosenblatt Stadium.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 22, 2002, with the final game of the double-elimination bracket.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Texas defeated South Carolina 12–6 to win its fifth championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2002 season marked the fifty sixth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series was held in Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Texas claiming their fifth championship with a 12–6 win over South Carolina in the final.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2003 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 16, 2003.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2003 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2003 College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 23, 2003, with the final game of the best-of-three championship series, the first such championship series used at the College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Rice defeated Stanford two games to one to claim its first championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Three programs joined Division I prior to the 2003 season– Gardner-Webb, which had been a provisional member; Savannah State, which had been a Division II independent; and IPFW, which had been a provisional member.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Howard dropped its baseball program following the 2002 season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Sacramento State, which had been a member of the Big West Conference, became a Division I independent.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Bowling Green, which had played in the East Division of the Mid-American Conference, moved to the West Division.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2003 season marked the fifty seventh NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Rice claiming their first championship with a two games to one series win over Stanford in the final.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **2003 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was held May 30 through June 23, 2003 to conclude the 2003 NCAA Division I baseball season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Sixty-four NCAA Division I college baseball teams met after having played their way through a regular season, and for some, a conference tournament, to play in the NCAA tournament.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament culminated with 8 teams in the College World Series at historic Rosenblatt Stadium in Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] ESPN, which held the rights to the College World Series, began televising super regional games in 2003.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] As part of the contract with ESPN, four super regionals would begin on Friday and run through Sunday, while the other four super regionals would begin Saturday and run through Monday.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The 2003 College World Series saw a format change and the championship was decided by a best-of-three series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] From 1950 through 1987, the College World Series was a true double elimination tournament.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] From 1988 through 2002, there were two double elimination pools, with the winner of each facing off in a one game championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] In the 2003 championship series, Rice defeated Stanford two games to one.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] John Hudgins became the 16th player to win the College World Series Most Outstanding Player Award from a losing team.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Conference champions from 30 Division I conferences earned automatic bids to regionals.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The remaining 34 spots were awarded to schools as at-large invitees.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Houston Super Regional was hosted by Rice at Reckling Park.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The following players were members of the College World Series All-Tournament Team.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2004 NCAA Division I baseball season** play of college baseball in the United States, organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 16, 2004.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2004 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2004 College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 27, 2004, with the final game of the best of three championship series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Cal State Fullerton defeated Texas two games to none to claim its fourth championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Three programs joined Division I for the 2004 season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Dallas Baptist and Northern Colorado joined from Division II, while Utah Valley joined from the NJCAA.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two programs left Division I prior to the start of the season– Drexel, which dropped its varsity baseball program, and Morris Brown, which discontinued its varsity athletics program.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Both the Ohio Valley Conference (OVC) and the Big South Conference (Big South) added two teams entering the season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The OVC added Jacksonville State and Samford, both from the Atlantic Sun Conference (A-Sun).
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The Big South added Birmingham–Southern, an independent, and VMI, a former Southern Conference (SoCon) member.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] To compensate for these moves, the A-Sun added Lipscomb, an independent, and the SoCon added Elon from the Big South.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two other schools realigned prior to the start of the season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] UMBC moved from the Northeast Conference to the America East Conference, and Centenary moved from being an independent to the Mid-Continent Conference.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Both the Colonial Athletic Association, which had competed in American and Colonial divisions, and the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference, which had competed in North and South divisions, eliminated their divisional formats.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2004 season marked the fifty eighth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Cal State Fullerton claiming their fourth championship with a two games to none series win over Texas in the final.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **2004 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was held from June 4 through June 27, 2004.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament culminates with 8 teams in the College World Series at historic Rosenblatt Stadium in Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] In the 58th College World Series and the 55th series held in Omaha, the Cal State Fullerton Titans rode the arm of Jason Windsor, named the Series' Most Outstanding Player, to prevail over the field and claim the 2004 National Championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Titans won Bracket II with a 3–1 record and went on to sweep Bracket I winner Texas in two games to claim the title.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Windsor picked up two complete game victories and a save, and threw more than 300 pitches in the series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Ricky Romero also recorded two wins for the Titans.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Hosted by Long Beach State at Blair Field.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2005 NCAA Division I baseball season** play of college baseball in the United States, organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 21, 2005.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2005 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2005 College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 26, 2005, with the final game of the best of three championship series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Texas defeated Florida two games to none to claim its sixth championship.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Four programs joined Division I for the 2005 season, all of which joined from Division II.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The four new Division I members were Longwood, North Dakota State, South Dakota State, and UC Davis.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two programs left Division I following the 2004 season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Pace, formerly an Independent, dropped to Division II.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Detroit, formerly a member of the Horizon League, discontinued its varsity baseball program.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The Atlantic Coast Conference added two members prior to the 2005 season.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Miami, previously an Independent, and Virginia Tech, previously a member of the Big East Conference, both joined the conference.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Division I's four new members, Longwood, North Dakota State, South Dakota State, and UC Davis, all became independents.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2005 season marked the fifty ninth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Texas claiming their sixth championship with a two games to none series win over Florida in the final.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] Owens played football and baseball at St.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] Lawrence and was drafted in the 25th round of the 1987 MLB draft.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] He played two seasons in the Chicago Cubs organization, reaching Class A.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] He then turned to coaching, serving as an assistant baseball and football coach at Ithaca Bombers.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] The following season, he earned a head coaching position with the Cortland Red Dragons baseball team, where he remained for eight seasons.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] He then coached at Le Moyne before becoming head coach at Bryant.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] In 2013, he led the Bulldogs to the NCAA tournament and was recognized as the ABCA Northeast Region Coach of the Year.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] Owens has won nine conference Coach of the Year Awards.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] At Cortland, he was named SUNYAC Coach of the Year in 1993, 1994, 1995, and 1998; at Le Moyne, MAAC Coach of the Year in 2004 and 2006; and at Bryant, NEC Coach of the Year in 2012, 2013, and 2014.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] On June 26, 2019, Steve Owens was announced as the new head coach of the Rutgers baseball program, replacing Joe Litterio whose contract was not renewed.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] This table depicts Owens' record as an NCAA head coach.
[src:steve-owens-baseball/steve-owens-baseball] Bryant was ineligible for postseason play as they were in transition to Division I.
